LX. The leaves of these plants differ as do the leaves of trees : in shortness or length of stalk‚ in the narrowness of the leaf itself, in its size, and further in the corners, and indentations3 smell and blossom differ also. The blossom lasts longer on some of them, which flower one part at a time, on ocimum for example, and on heliotropium, aphace and onochilis. Many of these plants, like certain trees, have leaves that never die, the chief being heliotropium, adiantum, hulwort.
